### TITLE ###
TypedLocalAssignmentNarrowsToRHS
### DESCRIPTION ###
`x: int? = 5` narrows x from declared int? to int via the assignment
(value type). Subsequent if-null-narrowing has nothing to strip.
### INPUT ###
x: int? = 5
y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  y @ 2:1 -> <no-type>
  x @ 2:5 -> int

# Symbol types
  x (local): int?
  y (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
TypedLocalReassignWidensBackToDeclared
### DESCRIPTION ###
After `x: int? = 5; if cond: x = something_optional()`, the second
assignment widens x back toward the declared type (int? again,
since RHS is int?).
### INPUT ###
fn maybe_int() -> int?:
    return null

x: int? = 5
if true:
    x = maybe_int()
y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 4:1 -> <no-type>
  x @ 6:5 -> <no-type>
  maybe_int @ 6:9 -> fn() -> int?
  y @ 7:1 -> <no-type>
  x @ 7:5 -> int?

# Symbol types
  maybe_int (fn): fn() -> int?
  x (local): int?
  y (local): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
TypedLocalRHSMismatchDoesNotNarrow
### DESCRIPTION ###
RHS that isn't assignable to the declared type fires a Hint
diagnostic; the frame stays at Declared (so downstream reads
don't cascade).
### INPUT ###
x: int = "wrong"
y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  y @ 2:1 -> <no-type>
  x @ 2:5 -> int

# Symbol types
  x (local): int
  y (local): int

# Diagnostics
  [hint] RAD30001 @ 1:10 - Value of type 'str' is not assignable to declared type 'int'
### TITLE ###
TypedLocalUntypedReassignIsClean
### DESCRIPTION ###
Regression lock: an untyped reassignment after a typed declaration
is fine. Previously the declared type was preserved for line 1, but
we want to confirm line 2 produces no diagnostic - and that the
symbol's declared type doesn't drift.
### INPUT ###
bb: int = 5
bb = 6
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  bb @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  bb @ 2:1 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  bb (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
TypedLocalRedeclarationWithDifferentTypeIsRejected
### DESCRIPTION ###
A second typed declaration of the same name is an error - the
declared type is part of the binding's contract and can't be
retroactively rewritten. The intermediate untyped reassignment on
line 2 stays clean; only line 3 is flagged.
### INPUT ###
bb: int = 5
bb = 6
bb: str = "hi"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  bb @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  bb @ 2:1 -> <no-type>
  bb @ 3:1 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  bb (local): int

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD40011 @ 3:1 - Cannot re-declare 'bb' with a type annotation (originally declared on line 1); drop ': str' to reassign
  [hint] RAD30001 @ 3:11 - Value of type 'str' is not assignable to declared type 'int'
### TITLE ###
TypedLocalRedeclarationSameTypeIsRejected
### DESCRIPTION ###
Same-type re-declaration is also flagged - it's almost always
leftover scaffolding from an edit, and treating both shapes the
same keeps the rule simple to teach.
### INPUT ###
bb: int = 5
bb: int = 6
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  bb @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  bb @ 2:1 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  bb (local): int

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD40011 @ 2:1 - Cannot re-declare 'bb' with a type annotation (originally declared on line 1); drop ': int' to reassign
